values.comments:
This is the beginners’ course in Modern Standard Arabic (MSA). It introduces the students to the speaking, listening, reading and writing skills in the standard means of communication in the Arab World. The course is proficiency based, implying that all activities within the course are aimed at placing the student in the context of the native-speaking environment from the very beginning. Evaluation is done by the more traditional testing methods (vocabulary tests, dictations, grammar and translation exercises). By the end of this course, students are expected to range in proficiency from Novice High to Intermediate Low.&#8232;&#8232;

Students commented that the course in general lacked a set structure. They found the textbook to be unhelpful, and thought there was too much material covered in a single semester. The fast pace of the course allowed students no time to learn or memorize newly learned material. Several students commented that they were “never able to gain a good estimate on how [their] progress in the language was because [they] never got any real substantive grades back.”&#8232;&#8232;

Professor Jasim, according to students, is “quite eccentric, but lovable and effective as a professor.” One student commented that she would often “vocalize her frustration with the Penn Arabic program, give up, and start teaching whatever she wanted,” worsening the disorganized structure of the class. Despite her frequent complaints about the lack of “colored chalk” in the classroom, however, she created a fun environment for students.&#8232;&#8232;

Students found the class to be packed with too much material, and it was difficult for beginners to “master pronunciation.” Many students commented that the class was more focused on grammar and that they did not learn real conversation.
